snippet.textDisplay: I only fly RC model helicopters, but the description of that heli descending VERY rapidly sounds to me like an engine failure had occurred and the pilot was trying to perform an auto-rotation maneuver where you descend with negative blade pitch very quickly then pull up and flare the heli at the last second to touch down.... only thing is, he couldn't see exactly where the ground was, and smashed into the hillside in the fog before he began to flare (or perhaps just as he began to flare, as the flare does involve transitioning into forward flight again in order to achieve lift from the spinning rotors). I can't think of any other reason the pilot would have descended that fast.... heli's with no engine power (or losing engine power) can still land safely using an auto-rotation maneuver, but you have to time it just right right before you pancake into the ground or else you will pancake into the ground! .

snippet.textDisplay: All I keep playing in my head is all these victims spending a cheerful happy night with their loved ones that Saturday. Wake up Sunday morning saying see you later and I love you to their families and last moments are clutching tight to each other on a chopper in thick fog about to crash at almost 200 Miles an hour.  It's making me think of Paul Walker, Astronauts from the Challenger space shuttle, golfer Payne Stewart,  Dale Earnhardt,  Buddy Holly , Ritchie Valens, JP Richardson, Aaliyah . . . . . I know death is part of life but OMG , the devastation , God Bless the families and loved ones and lets just all take time to love our spouses,  kids, life and the God given purpose we have been given even more . Please take nothing for granted , Moment of silence for all the victims,  in Jesus Name I ask that You provide the healing, strength and hope that will help the loved ones involved know that you are their guidance of light to turn this pain into power . We are all praying and sending encouragement to let the families know we are with you and will help you get thru it . Con Tu Adios , Te Llevas Mi Corazon aka With your farewell , you take with you My Heart . We will see you at Heaven's Gate.  Last thought in Vin Diesel's words : "You will always be with me and you will always be my brother "

snippet.textDisplay: For those who keep asking, the black "Mamba" helicopter was indeed the same helicopter that crashed. For his final game in April 2016, the helicopter had been specially decorated as a photo op. On that day it had been decorated (most likely "wrapped") with a black snakeskin pattern and his logo. Kobe never owned a helicopter; he leased the one they crashed in. Thus why the black decorations were never kept.

snippet.textDisplay: I have a background working as a stage manager in Hollywood. After the "Twilight Zone The Movie" helicopter accident (where 3 people, 2 of those being small children) the LAFD (Los Angeles Fire Department), the California State Film Commission and L.A. Film Permit Office, issued a Helicopter Safety Protocol Manual. I worked around helicopters and flew in them. They were used for camera, in scenes and for stunts etc. The day this pilot flew, the conditions were unacceptable. Foggy weather / low visibility. The helicopter should have never taken off. But there was a basketball game that morning (for 13 to 14 year olds) so there was pressure to get to the game, so they took the risk that ended 9 lives, including women and children. When Kobe's helicopter was in a holding pattern (as shown in the video above) hovering for 15 minutes near Burbank, the pilot and Kobe should have set the helicopter down and called for a limo or town car. It was a Sunday. There were empty parking lots every where to land in. But Kobe became complacent having flown so often for years. Why didn't he and the others stay in a hotel near the game a night or two before? Why didn't Kobe own a condo in that area? Small aircraft (including most especially helicopters) can be very dangerous, even with experienced pilots in good weather. I no longer fly in them. Even with friends that own small aircraft. Just far too dangerous. This was about taking the weather for granted. And major negligence on the part of Kobe, the pilot and in the end, the parents too. Very sad.

snippet.textDisplay:
Sometimes, as a pilot, we are under pressure to meet the demands of the customer to a point where we push our skills maybe beyond our limits, and we don't rationally think things through. Better off telling the customer that you refuse to fly in the name of safety, but if you want to fly, then get yourself a pilot that is intimidated enough to throw caution into the wind to bend to your demands. As a pilot, you would probably lose your job, but you won't lose your life!!!
The blame will go on the pilot with this one unfortunately, but as someone has already stated, he lost his life too!
